# Twelve Doors — the sawtooth, unhidden. Reverb stays low the whole
# piece; the richness is two detuned saws per voice and register
# space, not wash.
#
# The harmony is one trick done patiently: D4 and F#4 are pedal tones
# through the entire cycle while the top voice walks C#5 - B4 - A4 -
# and then Bb4, turning G major into G minor(maj7) with a single
# semitone. Only one voice ever moves into the darkness, which is why
# it feels inevitable instead of theatrical. The bridge finally spends
# the A# leading tone it has been withholding.
#
# The melody never announces itself: it enters after the chords have
# played a full cycle alone, on the "and" of the beat, soft attack,
# darker filter than the chords — and then it HOLDS while the harmony
# moves underneath, so the suspensions do the demanding for it. Its
# one big gesture: in the last cycle it lands directly on Bb5, the
# borrowed note, doubled an octave up by the chime.
#
# Effects move at section scale (chorus exists only in the bridge,
# one tape splice before the last cycle, reverb blooms only for the
# coda) — dynamic, but every sound is recognizably the same machine.

bpm 104
gate 0.9

automate lfo_rate
0.8
automate lfo_pitch
3
automate lfo_shape
0.5
automate chorus_depth
0.35
automate spring
0.06
automate reverb_decay
0.6
automate tape_wow
0.12
automate tape_flutter
0.08
automate tape_drive
0.15

track chords vel=0.6 patch=rawchord
[B2 D4 F#4]:8
